## SO1C

What is $\mathrm{SO}_1ℂ$?

%

## SO2C

What is $\mathrm{SO}_2ℂ$?

%

$ℂ^{≠ 0}$, the complex plane with one
point removed.

[#LieGroup]()

## SO3C

What is the double covering of
$\mathrm{SO}_3ℂ$?

%

$\mathrm{SL}_2ℂ$.

1. Take $3$-dim base space
   $V := 𝔰𝔩_2ℂ$.
2. Set the symmetric bilinear form
   $V × V → ℂ, \ (X, Y) ↦ \mathrm{tr}(XY)$.

3. The form is non-degenerate.
4. The isometric action
   $\mathrm{SL}_2ℂ → \mathrm{SO}(V), \ g ↦ g⁻¹ (-) g$.

5. The kernel is exactly $± I$.

[#LieGroup]()

## SO4C

What is the double covering of
$\mathrm{SO}_4ℂ$?

%

$(\mathrm{SL}_2ℂ)^2$.

1. Take $4$-dim base space
   $V := 𝔤𝔩_2ℂ$.
2. Set the symmetric bilinear form
   $V × V → ℂ, \ (X, Y) ↦ \det(X ⋅ \mathrm{Adj}(Y))$.

3. The form is non-degenerate.
4. The isometric action
   $(\mathrm{SL}_2ℂ)^2 → \mathrm{SO}(V), \ (g,h) ↦ g (-) h⁻¹$.
5. The kernel is exactly $± I$.

[#LieGroup]()

## SO5C

What is the double covering of
$\mathrm{SO}_5ℂ$?

%

$\mathrm{Sp}_4ℂ$.

1. Take $5$-dim base space
   $V ⊆ \mathrm{SL}_4ℂ$, where
   $\begin{pmatrix}
                      A & B \\ C&D
                  \end{pmatrix} ∈ V : (A=D^T) ∧ (B+B^T = C+C^T = O) ∧ (\mathrm{tr}(A) = 0)$.
2. Set the symmetric bilinear form
   $V × V → ℂ, \ (X, Y) ↦ \mathrm{tr}(XY)$.

3. The form is non-degenerate.
4. The isometric action
   $\mathrm{Sp}_4ℂ → \mathrm{SO}(V), \ g ↦ g (-) (Jg^TJ^{-1})$.
5. The kernel is exactly $± I$.

[#LieGroup]()

## SO6C

What is the double covering of
$\mathrm{SO}_6ℂ$?

%

$\mathrm{SL}_4ℂ$.

1. Take $6$-dim base space $⋀^2 ℂ ^4$.
2. Set the symmetric bilinear form
   $V × V → ℂ, \ (a∧ b, c∧ d) ↦ \mathrm{tr}(a ∣ b ∣ c ∣ d)$.

3. The form is non-degenerate.
4. The isometric action
   $\mathrm{SL}_4ℂ → \mathrm{SO}(V), \ g ↦ [a ∧ b ↦ ga ∧ gb]$.
5. The kernel is exactly $± I$.

## SO21

What is $\mathrm{SO}(2,1)$?

%

$\mathrm{SL}_2ℝ$.

1. Take $3$-dim base space
   $V := 𝔰𝔩_2ℝ$.
2. Set the symmetric bilinear form
   $V × V → ℝ, \ (X, Y) ↦ \mathrm{tr}(XY)$.

3. The form is non-degenerate, with
   inertia $(2,1)$.
4. The isometric action
   $\mathrm{SL}_2ℝ → \mathrm{SO}(V), \ g ↦ g⁻¹ (-) g$.

5. The kernel is exactly $± I$.

## SO31

What is the double covering of
$\mathrm{SO}(3,1)$?

%

$\mathrm{SL}_2ℂ$.

1. Take $4$-dim base space $V ⊆ 𝔤𝔩_2$,
   where
   $V = \left\{\begin{pmatrix}
                      a & b ⋅ i \\ c ⋅ i & \overline a
                  \end{pmatrix}\right\}$.

2. Set the symmetric bilinear form
   $V × V → ℝ, \ (X,Y) ↦ \mathrm{Re}(\mathrm{tr}(X ⋅ \overline Y))$.
3. The form is non-degenerate, with
   inertia $(3,1)$.
4. The isometric action
   $\mathrm{SL}_2ℂ ↦ \mathrm{SO}(V), \ g ↦ g(-)\overline {g^{-1}}$.
5. The kernel is exactly $± I$.

## SO22

What is the double covering of
$\mathrm{SO}(2,2)$?

%

$(\mathrm{SL}_2ℝ)^2$.

1. Take $4$-dim base space
   $V := 𝔤𝔩_2ℝ$.
2. Set the symmetric bilinear form
   $V × V → ℝ, \ (X, Y) ↦ \det(X ⋅ \mathrm{Adj}(Y))$.

3. The form is non-degenerate, with
   inertia $(2,2)$.
4. The isometric action
   $(\mathrm{SL}_2ℝ)^2 → \mathrm{SO}(V), \ (g,h) ↦ g (-) h⁻¹$.
5. The kernel is exactly $± I$.
